window.ACTT=window.ACTT||{};
window.ACTT.procedures={
  id:'procedures',
  title:'Procedures',
  subtitle:'Chapter 5 — Advanced Procedures',
  chapter:5,
  intro:'<p>This chapter converts the decision pathways from the previous chapter into hands-on action. The focus is not simply identifying when a procedure belongs in the plan; it is understanding how to set it up, perform it, confirm that it worked, and then continue caring for the patient afterward. Because the intended use case is a Royal Canadian Navy Physician Assistant working at sea, every procedure is framed through a practical lens: limited personnel, finite stock, ship movement, delayed evacuation, and the need to maintain the intervention over time.</p>'+
  '<h3>Purpose of This Chapter</h3>'+
  '<p>The aim of this chapter is to make the major ACTT procedures usable at the bedside. Each section is built to answer the practical questions that matter under pressure: when to do the procedure, when not to do it, what equipment to gather, how to prepare the patient and team, what sequence to follow, how to confirm success, and what immediate complications to expect.</p>'+
  '<ul><li>Translate high-risk procedures into repeatable bedside sequences.</li>'+
  '<li>Emphasize execution, confirmation, and reassessment rather than theory alone.</li>'+
  '<li>Integrate medication, monitoring, and post-procedure care into the same workflow.</li>'+
  '<li>Adapt each procedure to an at-sea, prolonged-care setting where the intervention may need to be maintained for hours.</li></ul>'+
  '<h3>How to Use This Chapter</h3>'+
  '<p>This chapter should be read like a working checklist. During study, it can be used to rehearse the order of actions. During practical preparation, it can be used to build equipment checklists, role assignments, and mental models for complications. In real use, the value of the chapter is in its structure: indication, setup, execution, confirmation, and aftercare.</p>'+
  '<ul><li>Review the indication first. A technically correct procedure performed for the wrong reason can still harm the patient.</li>'+
  '<li>Read the setup and backup plan before the step-by-step technique.</li>'+
  '<li>Treat confirmation and reassessment as part of the procedure, not optional extras.</li>'+
  '<li>If evacuation is delayed, transition quickly from procedure completion to maintenance planning.</li></ul>'+
  '<h3>Standard Procedure Format</h3>'+
  '<p>For consistency, every procedure in this chapter follows the same format. This makes the chapter easier to learn and faster to use under stress. The repeated structure also helps identify what is missing if the team is rushing: indication, equipment, backup plan, confirmation, or post-procedure monitoring.</p>'+
  '<ul><li>Purpose and clinical role</li><li>Indications</li><li>Contraindications and cautions</li><li>Required equipment</li><li>Team preparation and patient preparation</li><li>Landmarking and anatomy</li><li>Step-by-step technique</li><li>Confirmation of success</li><li>Immediate post-procedure management</li><li>Complications and troubleshooting</li><li>At-sea and delayed-MEDEVAC considerations</li><li>Medication needs relevant to the procedure</li></ul>'+
  '<h3>Pre-Procedure Fundamentals</h3>'+
  '<p>Before any invasive procedure, there are recurring fundamentals that determine whether the intervention runs smoothly or turns into a cascade of avoidable problems. These fundamentals apply to nearly every procedure in ACTT.</p>'+
  '<h4>Immediate Pre-Procedure Assessment</h4>'+
  '<p>Confirm the indication and urgency before starting. Ask whether the procedure is definitive, temporizing, or only a bridge to something else. If the patient is crashing, there may be no time for a full setup, but there is still time to state the indication, identify the immediate threat, and commit to the most direct life-saving action.</p>'+
  '<ul><li>Reassess airway, breathing, and circulation before starting.</li>'+
  '<li>Identify whether the patient is too unstable to delay for ideal preparation.</li>'+
  '<li>Clarify whether the procedure is expected to fix the problem or only buy time.</li>'+
  '<li>If a competing threat is greater than the indication for the procedure, address the greater threat first.</li></ul>'+
  '<h4>Team Preparation</h4>'+
  '<p>A short briefing improves success rates and reduces errors. In invasive procedures, even a ten-second statement of plan, backup, and failure point can prevent major delays. The operator should say what is about to happen, what the backup plan is, and what the team should announce if deterioration occurs.</p>'+
  '<ul><li>Assign an operator, assistant, medication handler, and monitor watcher if staffing permits.</li>'+
  '<li>State the primary plan and the immediate rescue plan out loud.</li>'+
  '<li>Confirm who is responsible for suction, oxygen, medication, and securing the device afterward.</li>'+
  '<li>Use closed-loop communication so critical actions are confirmed, not assumed.</li></ul>'+
  '<h4>Monitoring Requirements</h4>'+
  '<p>Monitoring is part of the procedure. SpO2, heart rhythm, blood pressure, and mental status should be observed before, during, and after the intervention. For airway procedures and sedation, EtCO2 should be used whenever available. The operator may be focused on the technical task, so one team member should be explicitly assigned to monitor trends and call out deterioration.</p>'+
  '<h4>Procedural Sedation and Analgesia Principles</h4>'+
  '<p>Not every urgent procedure allows time for full sedation, but pain control and anxiolysis still matter whenever feasible. The balance is between comfort and safety. Some procedures, such as a crashing chest decompression, may proceed with little or no analgesia because delay is more dangerous than pain. Others, such as chest tubes or shoulder reduction in a stable patient, benefit substantially from local anesthesia, ketamine, or other sedatives. After any sedative or opioid, airway and respiratory reassessment is mandatory.</p>'+
  '<h4>Infection Control and Sterility</h4>'+
  '<p>In austere or emergent settings, perfect sterility may not be possible, but deliberate clean technique still reduces complications. The operator should know which parts must remain as clean as possible: the insertion site, sterile instruments, and the device entering the patient. If the choice is between immediate life-saving action and waiting for ideal sterility, life-saving action takes priority, but contamination should still be minimized.</p>',
  sections:[
    {
      id:'rsi',
      title:'RSI Setup and Execution',
      content:'<p>Rapid Sequence Intubation (RSI) is used to establish a definitive airway quickly while minimizing aspiration risk and reducing prolonged struggling for the airway. Within ACTT, RSI is not only an airway procedure; it is also a structured sequence that depends on preparation, attempt discipline, rescue planning, and post-intubation management.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>GCS 8 or less, or inability to protect the airway.</li>'+
      '<li>Respiratory failure or exhaustion requiring controlled oxygenation and ventilation.</li>'+
      '<li>Severe agitation or combativeness preventing safe care when sedation alone is inadequate.</li>'+
      '<li>Anticipated airway deterioration such as inhalation injury or progressive facial swelling.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Massive facial trauma, complete upper airway obstruction, or anatomy that makes oral intubation effectively impossible may require immediate surgical airway instead.</li>'+
      '<li>Do not continue repeated attempts when the airway is predicted difficult and oxygenation is worsening.</li>'+
      '<li>Ketamine used for RSI should be paired with a paralytic when the plan is formal intubation; ketamine alone can increase laryngospasm risk.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Laryngoscope or video laryngoscope, appropriately sized endotracheal tube, bougie or stylet.</li>'+
      '<li>Bag-valve-mask, oxygen source, suction, and EtCO2 confirmation device.</li>'+
      '<li>Induction and paralytic medications drawn up, labeled, and immediately available.</li>'+
      '<li>Backup airway device and cricothyroidotomy kit opened or at arm\'s reach before the first attempt.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Confirm the indication, assign roles, and state the failed airway plan out loud.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Position the patient to maximize view and ventilation, and pre-oxygenate with 100 percent oxygen for 3\u20135 minutes when time allows.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Prepare suction and clear blood, secretions, or vomit before laryngoscopy if present.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Administer the induction agent, then the paralytic in planned RSI sequence.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">5</div><div class="ps-text">Perform laryngoscopy and place the tube using bougie or stylet support as needed.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">6</div><div class="ps-text">Inflate the cuff immediately after placement and begin controlled ventilation.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">7</div><div class="ps-text">Respect attempt limits: one attempt in a difficult airway, two attempts in a non-difficult airway only if oxygenation remains acceptable.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">8</div><div class="ps-text">If the permitted attempts fail or the patient cannot be oxygenated, move immediately to the rescue airway plan rather than repeating low-yield attempts.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Use EtCO2 to confirm tracheal placement as the strongest immediate confirmation tool.</li>'+
      '<li>Check chest rise, bilateral breath sounds, and tube depth marking.</li>'+
      '<li>Secure the tube well, then set initial ventilation targets based on the clinical problem.</li>'+
      '<li>Begin ongoing sedation after intubation; an intubated patient still requires analgesia and sedation.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Endotracheal Intubation Optimization</h4>'+
      '<p>RSI is only as good as the mechanics supporting first-pass success. The course material emphasizes difficult airway prediction and deliberate techniques to improve glottic view and reduce failed attempts.</p>'+
      '<p><strong>Airway Assessment:</strong> Use LEMON to predict difficult laryngoscopy and BONES to predict difficult bag-mask ventilation. The practical value is not academic scoring; it is deciding before the first attempt whether you should expect a poor view, a poor bagging situation, or both.</p>'+
      '<p><strong>View Optimization:</strong></p>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Use positioning and external laryngeal manipulation, including BURP where useful, to improve glottic view.</li>'+
      '<li>Apply the practical concepts often summarized as the \'Kovacs Kata\': optimize neck and head position, improve hand mechanics, manage the epiglottis deliberately, and adjust by slight pull-back if the tube trajectory is poor.</li>'+
      '<li>Use a bougie early when only a partial view is obtained rather than persisting with a poor blind tube pass.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<p><strong>Tube Confirmation and Securement:</strong> Confirmation does not end with one good breath. The tube must stay where it belongs. In burn patients, adhesive tape may fail on injured skin, so circumferential ties or other securement methods are safer.</p>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Esophageal intubation: suspect if no EtCO2, poor chest rise, and rapid desaturation. Remove and reattempt only if still within the permitted attempt plan.</li>'+
      '<li>Hypoxia: pause, re-oxygenate, suction, and reassess before further attempts.</li>'+
      '<li>Hypotension after induction: support perfusion immediately and reconsider sedation burden.</li>'+
      '<li>Tube dislodgement after successful placement: prevent with proper securement and deliberate handling.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>Pick the room, not just the moment.</strong> Before induction, ask whether this is the best compartment you will have. A treatment space with a secured deck, usable lighting, reachable suction, an oxygen source, and room for a second provider at the head is worth a 60&ndash;90 second delay to reach. Attempting RSI in a passageway or over a stretcher in the middeck is a failure multiplier you choose, not one you inherit.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Orient the patient to the long axis of the ship.</strong> In rough seas, rolling motion (beam-on swell) will throw a laterally-oriented head off the line of sight more than pitching. Position the casualty head-to-bow or head-to-stern whenever possible. Brake every roller on the stretcher, chock it, and strap the casualty across the forehead so ship motion does not rotate the airway axis mid-intubation.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Pre-stage the failed-airway plan physically, not mentally.</strong> The bougie, second laryngoscope with a fresh blade, LMA/iGel of the right size, and the open cricothyroidotomy tray must be on the bed or in the operator\'s hand &mdash; not "in the cupboard" and not "Sick Bay can grab it." If the cric tray is a five-second reach away, the plan is complete; if it is ten seconds away, it is not.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Pre-oxygenate longer than you would ashore.</strong> Ship motion, anxiety, and limited apneic oxygenation tolerance in sailors with variable fitness levels all shrink the safe apnea window. 3&ndash;5 minutes of pre-oxygenation on a non-rebreather at 15 L/min, plus apneic oxygen via nasal cannula at 15 L/min throughout the attempt, buys a margin you will need.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Announce the attempt limit before the first blade passes the lips.</strong> State aloud: "One attempt, then bougie, then cric." Write it on the whiteboard or the back of a gloved hand. Fatigue, motion, and adrenaline all pull toward repeated low-yield attempts &mdash; a pre-committed plan is the only reliable counter.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Use a bougie from the first attempt.</strong> With movement-induced view instability, a bougie through a partial view is safer than trying for a perfect direct tube pass. Load the bougie before the blade enters the mouth.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secure the tube for the sea state that is coming, not the one you have now.</strong> Commercial tube holders, twill ties, or circumferential tape plus a bite block. After securement, record tube depth at the teeth/gum line in the chart and mark it on the tube itself with a pen. Every time the patient is repositioned, transferred, or extracted through a hatch, the depth is re-checked against that recorded number.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Post-intubation sedation and analgesia must start in the room where intubation occurred.</strong> A patient who wakes partially during a transfer through a passageway may self-extubate before reaching Sick Bay. Draw up and label the post-intubation sedation (fentanyl + midazolam or ketamine infusion, as per ACTT) before induction, not after.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Assign an airway watch by name for the entire hold.</strong> State who owns tube security, who owns suction, and who is the backup if that person is pulled away. If the ship goes to action stations or general quarters, the airway watch is still the airway watch &mdash; negotiate that with the chain of command before the situation arises.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Suction will save the tube more than the laryngoscope.</strong> Confirm the Yankauer is attached, tested, and within arm\'s reach. On a moving platform, a clogged or absent suction is the most common preventable cause of desaturation during handling and transfer.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>If the casualty must be moved after intubation,</strong> disconnect the ventilator only at the last second, hand-bag with capnography through the transfer, and re-confirm tube position and all ventilator settings at the destination. Write the transfer as a brief entry in the record: time, who was on the tube, whether anything changed.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Airway procedures require the operator to think in phases: induction, paralysis, confirmation, then post-intubation sedation. The tube is not the endpoint; sedation and ventilator management begin immediately after placement.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['algorithms/airway-failure','medications/ketamine','medications/succinylcholine','checklists/rsi'],
      sources:[
        {title:'ACTT 2026-01 Airway.pdf',file:'ACTT 2026-01 Airway .pdf',note:'Primary ACTT airway procedure source.'},
        {title:'RSI Check List and Intubation.pdf',file:'RSI Check List and Intubation.pdf'},
        {title:'Ressource for RSI.pdf',file:'Ressource for RSI.pdf'}
      ]
    },
    {
      id:'procedural-sedation',
      title:'Procedural Sedation and Analgesia',
      content:'<p>Procedural sedation enables short, painful bedside interventions while preserving protective reflexes and hemodynamic stability. This workflow integrates the ACTT procedural sedation presentation and the PA medical directive so it can be run quickly and safely at the bedside.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Short painful procedures requiring immobility (fracture or joint reduction, complex laceration repair, abscess I&amp;D, tube thoracostomy, emergency airway support).</li>'+
      '<li>Wound care or dressing changes that cannot be tolerated with local anesthesia alone.</li>'+
      '<li>Combative or severely anxious patients who are interfering with necessary medical care.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Age under 3 months or known/suspected schizophrenia (per directive).</li>'+
      '<li>Predicted difficult airway, obstructive sleep apnea, or high aspiration risk without a rescue plan.</li>'+
      '<li>Severe cardiorespiratory instability not yet addressed.</li>'+
      '<li>Inability to provide continuous monitoring or immediate airway rescue.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Pre-Sedation Setup</h4>'+
      '<p><span class="time-sensitive-badge">⏱ Time-Sensitive</span> All monitoring and equipment must be ready before first medication dose.</p>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><span class="warning-badge">Critical</span> Two qualified personnel (sedation/monitor and procedure operator) with roles and backup airway plan verbalized.</li>'+
      '<li>Consent and time-out completed; weight recorded for dosing; baseline vitals and fasting/aspiration risk noted.</li>'+
      '<li>IV access preferred and patent; oxygen source, suction, BVM with adjuncts, and SGA/ETT rescue equipment at bedside.</li>'+
      '<li>Monitoring on before first dose: SpO\u2082, BP, ECG, and EtCO\u2082 if available (cycle frequently during sedation).</li>'+
      '<li>Medications drawn up, diluted, labeled, and double-checked: ketamine (prepare 10 mg/mL syringes), optional midazolam in 0.5\u20132 mg IV increments, opioid analgesia only if needed, ondansetron prophylaxis considered.</li>'+
      '<li><span class="warning-badge amber">Caution</span> Reversal agents ready if applicable: naloxone for opioid-induced respiratory depression, flumazenil for selected benzodiazepine reversal.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">State the indication, target depth (anxiolysis, moderate, dissociative), and rescue plan. Assign a dedicated monitor separate from the proceduralist.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Apply monitoring, record baseline vitals, position the patient, and pre-oxygenate. Confirm suction and BVM are within reach.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Draw and label ketamine weight-based (1 mg/kg IV over 60 seconds or 4\u20135 mg/kg IM when IV delayed). Prepare small midazolam aliquots (0.5\u20132 mg IV) only as needed for anxiolysis or emergence reactions. Use opioid analgesia in small slow increments (for example, fentanyl 0.5\u20131 mcg/kg) if required.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Start capnography if available. Deliver the first ketamine dose slowly; avoid the dysphoric mid-range (0.3\u20130.8 mg/kg). Allow full onset before redosing to prevent dose stacking.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">5</div><div class="ps-text">Maintain continuous observation: one person focuses on airway/ventilation, secretions, and hemodynamics while the procedure proceeds.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">6</div><div class="ps-text">If airway tone decreases, use jaw thrust, repositioning, and suction. Provide BVM support early rather than waiting for desaturation.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">7</div><div class="ps-text">Document times, doses, responses, and any rescue interventions. Stop dosing once the target depth is reached.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">8</div><div class="ps-text">Transition to recovery: stop procedural stimulus, continue monitoring, and reassess every few minutes until the patient meets recovery criteria.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Monitoring and Recovery</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>During sedation: continuous observation with SpO\u2082 and ECG, BP cycling, and EtCO\u2082 when available (capnography catches apnea before oximetry if on oxygen).</li>'+
      '<li>Recovery: monitor at least every 5 minutes until awake, maintaining airway reflexes, stable vitals, controlled pain/nausea, and able to mobilize or has escort per policy.</li>'+
      '<li>Document total doses, complications, and discharge/transport instructions.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Rescue</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>Laryngospasm or apnea:</strong> suction, jaw thrust, BVM; consider paralytic and intubation if unresolved.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Hypotension:</strong> pause dosing, provide fluids; pressor support if clinically indicated.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Emergence reactions:</strong> small midazolam increments as needed.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Emesis/aspiration risk:</strong> suction promptly; place in lateral recovery position when feasible.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Hypersalivation:</strong> suction and positioning; rare need for anticholinergic adjunct.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<p>Shipboard sedation demands disciplined documentation of doses, timings, and responses so watch turnover remains safe. Limited staffing means the monitor and airway rescue plan must be explicit before starting. During delayed evacuation, plan for repeated reassessments, antiemetic use, and medication supply tracking.</p>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Notes</h4>'+
      '<p>Ketamine is the primary agent because it preserves airway reflexes and hemodynamic stability. Administer slowly to reduce laryngospasm risk. Midazolam and opioids are synergistic; use small increments and avoid stacking. Ondansetron prophylaxis reduces vomiting during recovery. Keep naloxone and flumazenil available when benzodiazepines or opioids are used.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['checklists/procedural-sedation','medications/analgesics','medications/sedatives','prolonged-holding/sedation-pain','algorithms/combative-patient','thresholds/medication-safety','pitfalls/medication-errors'],
      sources:[
        {title:'ACTT 2026-01 Procedural Sedation.pdf',file:'ACTT 2026-01 Procedural Sedation.pdf',note:'Primary ACTT procedural sedation source.'},
        {title:'PA_Procedural Sedation Med Directive (1).docx',file:'PA_Procedural Sedation Med Directive (1).docx'}
      ]
    },
    {
      id:'surgical-cric',
      title:'Surgical Cricothyroidotomy',
      content:'<p>Surgical cricothyroidotomy is the definitive rescue airway when oral access has failed or is not possible. In the ACTT context, this is the procedure that follows disciplined recognition of a true failed airway, not repeated ineffective laryngoscopy.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Cannot intubate and cannot oxygenate scenario.</li>'+
      '<li>Massive maxillofacial trauma blocking oral airway access.</li>'+
      '<li>Complete upper airway obstruction where the obstruction cannot be bypassed orally.</li>'+
      '<li>Failed airway after the permitted intubation attempts.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>In a crashing patient there are few absolute contraindications; delay is usually more dangerous than proceeding.</li>'+
      '<li>Landmarks may be distorted by obesity, swelling, or blood. Deliberate midline landmarking is critical.</li>'+
      '<li>False passage becomes more likely if the membrane is not clearly entered before tube insertion.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Scalpel, tracheal hook or bougie depending on technique, appropriately sized tracheostomy tube or endotracheal tube.</li>'+
      '<li>Suction, oxygen, ventilation device, EtCO2 device, and securement ties.</li>'+
      '<li>Assistant to stabilize the larynx and manage suction if available.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Palpate and stabilize the larynx, identifying thyroid cartilage, cricoid cartilage, and the membrane between them.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Make a vertical skin incision in the midline to improve exposure and preserve options if landmarks shift.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Enter the cricothyroid membrane with a horizontal puncture or controlled incision.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Use the chosen method to open the tract, such as hook or bougie-assisted entry.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">5</div><div class="ps-text">Insert the tube through the membrane into the trachea, inflate the cuff if present, and begin ventilation.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">6</div><div class="ps-text">Secure the tube immediately after confirmation.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Confirm with EtCO2, chest rise, and bilateral breath sounds.</li>'+
      '<li>Control bleeding as able and keep the field clear for reassessment.</li>'+
      '<li>Continue oxygenation and begin longer-term airway management planning.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>False passage if the tract is not truly in the trachea.</li>'+
      '<li>Bleeding obscuring the field and causing delay; suction must be ready.</li>'+
      '<li>Dislodgement if the tube is not well secured, especially during transport.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>This is likely your definitive airway for the entire hold.</strong> Unlike shore, there will be no OR conversion to a formal tracheostomy in the next 48 hours. Place the tube with the expectation that it is the airway until MEDEVAC &mdash; that changes how it must be secured, humidified, and cared for.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secretions are the biggest enemy on a prolonged cric.</strong> Without humidification, the airway dries, mucus plugs, and the tube occludes silently. Set up heat-moisture exchangers (HME) on the ventilator circuit or BVM immediately; schedule sterile saline instillation (1&ndash;3 mL) and suction every 1&ndash;2 hours for the first 12 hours, then based on secretion load. Document suction frequency and character of secretions.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Bleeding does not stop because you moved on.</strong> Cricothyroid bleeding can be occult &mdash; blood tracks down the tube rather than pooling visibly. Reassess the neck, dressing, and tube for fresh blood q30 min for the first 2 hours, then hourly. Low thresholds for circumferential neck exam during a delayed hold.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Redundant securement that survives deck movement.</strong> Tracheostomy twill ties around the neck plus a secondary anchor dressing. Check tie tension after any patient repositioning &mdash; ties that were snug when the patient was supine may become loose when the head is turned or the stretcher is tilted.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Pre-stage a replacement tube at the bedside.</strong> Accidental decannulation of a fresh cric is a catastrophe; the tract will not stay open. Have an identical or smaller replacement tube, a tracheal dilator or hemostat for stoma maintenance, and a BVM with face mask within arm\'s reach for oral rescue ventilation.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Sedation strategy must protect the tube.</strong> A semi-awake patient coughing against a 6.0 cric tube is a dislodgement risk. Continuous sedation (fentanyl + midazolam or ketamine infusion per ACTT) with frequent neuro/respiratory reassessment is more appropriate than bolus-based sedation that wears off between watches.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Ventilation volumes may need downward adjustment.</strong> A 6.0 cricothyroidotomy tube has higher resistance than a 7.5 ETT; expect higher peak pressures and consider smaller tidal volumes with higher rate if peak pressures climb.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Assign an airway watch by name for the entire hold.</strong> The airway is not a background task. One person owns tube security, suction, and immediate response to alarms. State the name, and the backup name, at every watch handover.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Tube changes are a 2-person procedure.</strong> If tube obstruction or failure requires replacement, do not attempt it alone. The second provider pre-oxygenates, hands tools, and is ready to rescue. Pre-plan this conversation before the emergency.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>MEDEVAC request should already be in motion.</strong> A surgical airway at sea is an automatic trigger for the highest-priority evacuation the mission allows. This conversation happens before the securement dressing is finished, not after.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Local anesthesia may not be practical in a crashing patient. Post-procedure sedation and analgesia are required once the airway is secured. Rescue medications including fluids, vasopressors, suction, oxygen, and rescue airway equipment should be considered part of the setup, not optional extras.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['algorithms/airway-failure','procedures/rsi','procedures/needle-cric'],
      sources:[
        {title:'Cricothyroidotomy.pdf',file:'Cricothyroidotomy.pdf',note:'Primary rescue airway procedure source.'},
        {title:'ACTT 2026-01 Airway.pdf',file:'ACTT 2026-01 Airway .pdf'}
      ]
    },
    {
      id:'needle-cric',
      title:'Needle Cricothyroidotomy',
      content:'<p>Needle cricothyroidotomy is a temporary bridge used when immediate rescue oxygenation is needed and a definitive airway is not yet in place. It is not a durable long-term airway plan.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Immediate cannot-intubate, cannot-oxygenate situation when a rapid temporizing airway is needed.</li>'+
      '<li>Bridge while preparing for definitive surgical airway or other airway rescue.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Limited ventilation capability means this is time-limited and should not be mistaken for definitive control.</li>'+
      '<li>Kinking, dislodgement, and inadequate ventilation are common failure modes.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>14-gauge catheter, syringe, connection adapter, oxygen source, and improvised or formal ventilation connection setup.</li>'+
      '<li>Backup definitive airway plan already identified before or immediately after placement.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Identify the cricothyroid membrane and stabilize the larynx.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Puncture the membrane with the catheter-over-needle at the appropriate angle, then alter the angle to advance the catheter into the airway.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Advance the catheter, remove the needle, and attach the ventilation adapter.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Begin oxygenation and assess immediately while preparing a definitive airway.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Watch for improved oxygenation and visible chest rise.</li>'+
      '<li>Do not stop at temporary improvement; proceed directly to definitive airway planning.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Catheter kinking or dislodgement can rapidly end the benefit.</li>'+
      '<li>Ventilation may be inadequate even if oxygenation briefly improves.</li>'+
      '<li>Subcutaneous air suggests malposition or air leak.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>This is a transoceanic crossing measured in minutes.</strong> A needle cric gives you oxygenation but very limited ventilation &mdash; CO<sub>2</sub> climbs steadily, and in a healthy adult you have roughly 15&ndash;30 minutes before hypercarbia and acidosis become the primary problem. At sea, that window is your conversion timeline, not your holding timeline.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Convert to a surgical airway in the same session.</strong> Do not move the patient out of the intubation space hoping things will improve. Open the surgical cric tray the moment the needle is in and begin conversion while the patient is still in the current position &mdash; every transfer through a hatch, ladder, or passageway with an unsecured bridge airway invites dislodgement.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Plan for hypoventilation as the dominant physiology.</strong> Even with 50 psi jet ventilation, CO<sub>2</sub> clearance is poor. If the patient is a TBI case, brief hypercarbia will worsen intracranial pressure &mdash; prioritize conversion urgency. If the patient is asthmatic or has obstructive physiology, exhalation may be catastrophically poor; let passive exhalation occur between jets.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Assign a dedicated hand to the catheter hub.</strong> Ship motion, BVM tugging, and intubation equipment crowding all conspire to kink or extract a 14 G catheter in the trachea. One person holds the hub flush to the skin with positive pressure against dislodgement throughout the bridge period &mdash; they do nothing else.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Pre-brief the whole room on what "conversion" means.</strong> State aloud: "We are on a needle for minutes only. Surgical cric is the next step, happening now." This prevents the team from mentally settling into the needle as the airway.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>If you cannot convert, document why and call teleconsult.</strong> Anatomy, bleeding, or equipment failure can stall conversion. Note the attempt and escalate the MEDEVAC request while continuing manual stabilization and oxygenation.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Rescue medications including fluids, vasopressors, suction, and oxygen should be immediately available. Transition to definitive airway management (and its associated medications for induction and sedation) should be planned concurrently.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['algorithms/airway-failure','procedures/surgical-cric','procedures/rsi']
    },
    {
      id:'needle-thoracostomy',
      title:'Needle Thoracostomy',
      content:'<p>Needle thoracostomy is an emergent decompression procedure for suspected tension pneumothorax. It is designed to relieve immediately life-threatening pressure, not to serve as final pleural management.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Respiratory distress with tension physiology such as unilateral absent breath sounds and hemodynamic instability.</li>'+
      '<li>Suspected tension pneumothorax during decompensation or cardiac arrest where delaying for imaging is unsafe.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>There are few true contraindications in an unstable patient, but wrong-site placement and wrong-diagnosis decompression are major practical risks.</li>'+
      '<li>If the patient does not improve, do not assume the diagnosis was wrong without reassessing technique and catheter function.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>14-gauge 3.25-inch catheter, antiseptic if available, gloves, and chest tube equipment prepared immediately after.</li>'+
      '<li>Operator must know the landmark before skin puncture; rushed guessing increases failure.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Choose the insertion site: second intercostal space mid-clavicular line or fourth/fifth intercostal space at the anterior- or mid-axillary line.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Prep the skin if time permits and identify the superior border of the rib below the target space to avoid the neurovascular bundle.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Insert the catheter over the superior rib margin into the pleural space until decompression is achieved.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Advance the catheter fully, remove the needle, and reassess immediately.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Expected findings include air release, improved oxygenation, improved blood pressure, or reduced distress.</li>'+
      '<li>If there is no improvement, reassess the site, depth, and whether the catheter remains patent.</li>'+
      '<li>Prepare for immediate transition to chest tube thoracostomy if the patient is salvageable.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Failed decompression due to short catheter, wrong landmark, or catheter obstruction.</li>'+
      '<li>Injury to underlying structures if inserted in the wrong location.</li>'+
      '<li>False reassurance after partial improvement; tension can recur quickly.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>Use a long catheter and confirm the length before you sail.</strong> The standard 14 G 5 cm catheter fails to reach the pleural space in roughly one-third of adult males. A 14&ndash;10 G, 8 cm (3.25 inch) catheter is the ACTT-preferred option; verify this is what is actually in your thoracostomy kit on every deployment, not what was ordered last year.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Prefer the 4th/5th ICS anterior-to-mid axillary line.</strong> Lateral access is now the ACTT-preferred approach and is mechanically easier on a moving platform: the casualty can be lying on the stretcher with one arm raised, the operator works from the side (not across the sternum), and the chest wall is thinnest there. Reserve 2nd ICS midclavicular for situations where lateral access is blocked.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secure the stretcher before the needle goes in.</strong> Brake the stretcher, chock it if there is deck roll, and assign a crew member to hold the casualty\'s shoulder and hip against the ship\'s motion. Count ribs deliberately; if time allows, mark the insertion point with a pen so it survives repositioning.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Insert over the superior rib margin and advance the catheter fully to the hub.</strong> A partial advancement leaves the catheter tip in the chest wall muscle &mdash; it will kink or retract on the next roll. Remove the needle, advance the catheter to the hub, and secure.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Expect a short lifespan and pre-stage the finger/chest tube tray.</strong> Plan the definitive chest tube in the same breath as you call for the needle. Movement, kinking, clotting, or accidental traction typically end needle effectiveness within minutes. At sea, the catheter is a transport bridge measured in single-digit minutes &mdash; not a holding solution.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Reassess after every movement.</strong> After each transfer through a hatch, ladder, or compartment door, recheck breath sounds, SpO<sub>2</sub>, work of breathing, ventilator resistance if intubated, and hemodynamics. Tension recurs silently on a sedated patient who cannot complain.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secure the hub and record placement.</strong> Tape the catheter hub flat to the skin with two strips forming an "H," cover with a transparent dressing so the entry site is visible, and document time, side, landmark used, and the name of the operator so recurrence and failure can be tracked across watch handovers.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Finger thoracostomy is a legitimate at-sea option.</strong> If the needle fails and a surgical chest tube is delayed, a small lateral incision with blunt finger entry into the pleural space reliably relieves tension and is easier on a moving platform than trying to rail-road a tube blindly. Convert to a formal chest tube once the casualty is in Sick Bay.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>In a crashing patient, this procedure typically proceeds without analgesia because delay is more dangerous than pain. Once the patient stabilizes, analgesia should be provided. Prepare for transition to chest tube thoracostomy and its associated sedation and local anesthesia needs.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['procedures/chest-tube','algorithms/tension-pneumothorax'],
      sources:[
        {title:'ACTT 2026-01 ATLS.pdf',file:'ACTT 2026-01 ATLS.pdf',note:'Primary thoracic trauma source.'},
        {title:'Setup - Pleurevac.pdf',file:'Setup - Pleurevac.pdf'}
      ]
    },
    {
      id:'chest-tube',
      title:'Chest Tube Thoracostomy',
      content:'<p>Chest tube thoracostomy is the definitive drainage procedure for pneumothorax, hemothorax, and other selected pleural collections. It converts a temporary decompression into a maintainable pleural drainage plan.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Pneumothorax requiring definitive drainage after needle decompression or because recurrence risk is high.</li>'+
      '<li>Hemothorax or ongoing pleural air or blood requiring controlled evacuation.</li>'+
      '<li>Persistent instability after needle decompression where definitive management is needed.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Coagulopathy and distorted anatomy increase risk but are often relative concerns in a life-threatening thoracic emergency.</li>'+
      '<li>Avoid clearly infected overlying tissue when possible, but life-saving access takes priority if no alternative exists.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Chest tube of appropriate size, scalpel, blunt clamp, sterile supplies, local anesthetic or sedation when feasible, sutures or securement, and drainage device such as a Pleurovac.</li>'+
      '<li>Monitoring, suction setup if used, and a plan for output tracking after insertion.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Pleurovac Setup and Initial Checks</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Connect the patient drainage tubing to the thoracic catheter, add sterile fluid to the air leak meter if the device requires it, and set suction only if ordered.</li>'+
      '<li>When suction is used, confirm the prescribed dial setting and increase the source until the suction indicator or orange float is visible.</li>'+
      '<li>Keep the drainage unit below chest level, avoid dependent loops or kinks, and leave the tube unclamped unless briefly changing the unit or specifically ordered.</li>'+
      '<li>Document a starting system picture: output amount and character, tidaling or fluctuation, and the highest bubbling column if an air leak is present.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Position the patient and identify the fifth intercostal space at the mid-axillary line.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Prep and drape, then make the skin incision over the rib line that supports safe pleural entry.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Use blunt dissection through the tissue planes and enter over the superior rib margin to avoid the neurovascular bundle.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Open the pleural space with controlled blunt entry and perform a finger sweep to confirm intrathoracic placement and exclude organ contact.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">5</div><div class="ps-text">Advance the tube into the pleural space, directing it appropriately for the expected pathology, then connect immediately to the drainage system.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">6</div><div class="ps-text">Secure the tube, dress the site, and reassess the patient and the function of the system.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Look for clinical improvement, expected tube output, and appropriate system behavior such as bubbling or fluid movement when relevant.</li>'+
      '<li>Expected tidaling or fluctuation supports a functioning system unless the lung is fully re-expanded; in a ventilated patient the pattern reverses.</li>'+
      '<li>Use the air leak meter at the bottom of the chamber and document the highest bubbling column if a leak is present.</li>'+
      '<li>Check securement, tube depth, drainage tubing alignment, and whether the system is functioning as intended.</li>'+
      '<li>Continue repeated reassessment because a technically placed tube can still fail later due to blockage or dislodgement.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Pleurovac Interpretation and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>No tidaling or sudden loss of drainage may mean a kink, clot, dependent loop, clamp, or a fully re-expanded lung; correct simple mechanical problems first and reassess.</li>'+
      '<li>Continuous or new bubbling should prompt tracing the system from insertion site to drain, tightening or taping loose connections, and distinguishing patient air leak from system leak.</li>'+
      '<li>If the suction indicator or orange float is not visible when suction is ordered, increase source suction and check for occluded or disconnected tubing; replace the drainage unit if malfunction persists.</li>'+
      '<li>Sudden increase in bloody drainage, abrupt character change, or patient deterioration despite system correction should trigger immediate escalation for hemorrhage, recurrent pneumothorax, or tube failure.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Misplacement, organ injury, persistent air leak, inadequate drainage, blocked tube, dependent loops, loss of suction, and accidental dislodgement are the major risks.</li>'+
      '<li>If the patient remains unstable, reassess for tube position, tube patency, system function, or an alternate diagnosis rather than assuming the procedure was sufficient.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>Give a prophylactic antibiotic at placement.</strong> Ceftriaxone 2 g IV x1 at the time of trauma chest tube insertion is the ACTT teaching. Stock a dedicated dose with the thoracostomy tray so it is not forgotten under pressure.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secure the Pleur-evac against ship motion like it is a piece of running rigging.</strong> Unit stays upright, below the chest, and lashed to a fixed point (stretcher rail, bunk frame, bulkhead cleat) with enough slack to allow patient repositioning but not enough to allow the unit to tip. A tipped Pleur-evac spills the water seal and loses function silently &mdash; brief the watch on what this looks like and what to do about it.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Redundant tube fixation.</strong> A primary suture (or commercial tube holder) plus a secondary anchoring dressing plus a circumferential chest wrap or body tube-holder strap. Mark the tube at the skin in ink so dislodgement is visible at a glance. Record the tube depth in the chart.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Build an output trend sheet at the bedside.</strong> Record drainage hourly for the first 4 hours, then every 2&ndash;4 hours. Document volume, color, and whether tidaling is present. A written trend beats memory every time, especially across a watch change.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Escalation triggers must be written and pre-committed.</strong> &gt; 1500 mL initial output, &gt; 200 mL/hr for 3&ndash;4 hours, sudden brisk output after a lull, persistent large air leak, or loss of tidaling with respiratory decline all trigger teleconsult and MEDEVAC escalation. Post these numbers at the bedside so the watch acts on them without waiting for the PA.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Plan transfers with the Pleur-evac as a package.</strong> Never clamp the tube for transport unless specifically ordered for a brief disconnection; clamping a leaking lung recreates the tension. During movement through tight spaces or up ladders, assign one crew member solely to the chest tube and drainage unit, keeping them below chest level and un-kinked.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Keep the dislodgement response drilled.</strong> Occlusive dressing taped on three sides if the tube comes out, immediate reassessment, a replacement tube kit on standby. Rehearse this with the junior med team member on every sail &mdash; a chest tube that comes out on the mid-watch at 0300 is a test of pre-drilled habits, not improvisation.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Atrium/Pleur-evac dry-suction units tolerate motion better than water-suction.</strong> If you have a choice in stock, prefer the dry-suction regulator for a small platform because it is less affected by roll and tilt. Confirm the unit in use on your deployment.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Plan for tube dwell times longer than ashore.</strong> MEDEVAC delay means the tube may be in place for 24&ndash;72+ hours. Build a daily site-care plan: dressing change if soiled, skin assessment at the entry, and stock check on replacement dressings and suture material.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Lidocaine is useful for chest tube placement as local anesthesia. The goal is not full comfort at all costs; it is enough local control to improve tolerance without delaying a necessary intervention. Sedation with ketamine or other agents may be appropriate in stable patients. After any sedative or opioid, airway and respiratory reassessment is mandatory.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['procedures/needle-thoracostomy','prolonged-holding/device-maintenance','pitfalls/thoracic-errors','medications/lidocaine','medications/ketamine'],
      sources:[
        {title:'Setup - Pleurevac.pdf',file:'Setup - Pleurevac.pdf',note:'Primary chest drainage setup guide.'},
        {title:'Pleurovac_Air Leak.pdf',file:'Pleurovac_Air Leak.pdf'},
        {title:'SU_CST_S1100Setup_PO_MC000098.pdf',file:'SU_CST_S1100Setup_PO_MC000098.pdf'}
      ]
    },
    {
      id:'io-access',
      title:'Intraosseous Access',
      content:'<p>Intraosseous (IO) access provides rapid vascular access when peripheral access fails or when delay is unacceptable. It allows delivery of fluids, blood products, and most emergency medications.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Cardiac arrest, severe shock, or urgent medication need when IV access is delayed or unsuccessful.</li>'+
      '<li>Adults after failed IV attempts or prolonged attempt time.</li>'+
      '<li>First-line access in selected pediatric emergency situations.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Do not use through a fractured target bone or a limb with a recent IO attempt in the same site region.</li>'+
      '<li>Site infection or inability to identify landmarks increases failure and complication risk.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>IO device and needle set, saline flush, pressure bag, extension tubing, securement, and preservative-free lidocaine for conscious patients.</li>'+
      '<li>Choose the site before opening the device and make sure backup access planning continues in parallel.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Identify the chosen site, prep it, and orient the device at the correct angle for that site.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Advance until the characteristic loss of resistance or \'pop\' indicates marrow cavity entry.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Remove the stylet, connect tubing, aspirate if possible, and flush aggressively to confirm patency.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Secure the line and apply pressure-assisted infusion if rapid flow is required.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">5</div><div class="ps-text">In a conscious patient, use lidocaine through the IO before forceful flushing or infusion to reduce severe infusion pain.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>A successful IO should flush relatively easily without soft tissue swelling.</li>'+
      '<li>Good flow often depends on a proper initial flush and pressure support, not the needle alone.</li>'+
      '<li>Reassess the site repeatedly for leakage, swelling, and pain.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Extravasation, compartment syndrome, failed marrow entry, bent needle, and poor flow are the main issues.</li>'+
      '<li>If fluids are not flowing, reassess whether the line was flushed properly before assuming the site is unusable.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>IO is a first-attempt option, not a last resort.</strong> On a moving deck with a shocked, cold, or combative sailor, the 60&ndash;90 seconds spent hunting a peripheral vein is often the most dangerous time in the resuscitation. If two honest attempts at a visible vein fail, or if the patient needs medication in the next 60 seconds, place the IO.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Humeral head is ACTT-preferred in trauma/shock.</strong> Higher flow rates (~5 L/hr pressurized vs. ~1 L/hr tibial), less interference with trauma workup, and it stays patent during CPR. Confirm landmarks are drilled and the EZ-IO 45 mm needle is in your kit for humeral use. Tibial is acceptable for smaller patients or when the humerus is inaccessible.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secure the hub aggressively.</strong> The EZ-IO hub is a known snag point in narrow passageways and during stretcher carries up ladders. Use the stabilizer dressing that comes with the kit plus an additional layer of tape; route the extension tubing in a service loop so pulls transmit to the tape, not the needle.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Give lidocaine before flushing the conscious patient.</strong> Preservative-free lidocaine 40 mg (2%) slow IO push, wait 60 seconds, then flush. An unmedicated conscious IO flush is genuinely traumatic and produces agitation the ship does not need.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Pressurize the bag to get real flow.</strong> Crystalloid through an IO by gravity alone is slow &mdash; use a pressure bag at 300 mmHg, or push 50 mL syringes of crystalloid by hand when rapid volume is needed. Document the infusion method in the chart.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Plan the conversion window.</strong> IO sites should be converted to durable IV access (peripheral or central) within 24 hours. At sea, build that conversion into the care plan on day one: it may mean an ultrasound-guided peripheral IV when the patient is stable, or waiting until MEDEVAC for central access. Record the IO placement time clearly so conversion does not drift past the window.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Watch for extravasation with every drug.</strong> On a moving platform, the humerus rotates with the arm and can dislodge. Any increased pain at the site, loss of flow, or soft tissue swelling means stop the infusion, reassess, and place a second access. Compartment syndrome of the arm from extravasated IO is a real complication.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Document which medications went IO.</strong> Almost all resuscitation drugs can be given IO, but dosing for vasopressors and antibiotics is identical to IV &mdash; there is no dose adjustment. Chart "IO" as the route so the receiving team knows.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Preservative-free lidocaine should be administered through the IO in conscious patients before forceful flushing or infusion to reduce severe infusion pain. Most emergency medications can be delivered via IO access. Any invasive procedure can precipitate hypotension, hypoxia, or worsening pain. Fluids, vasopressors, suction, oxygen, and rescue airway equipment should be considered part of the setup, not optional extras.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['medications/lidocaine','algorithms/vascular-access'],
      sources:[
        {title:'EZIO.pdf',file:'EZIO.pdf',note:'Primary IO device guide.'},
        {title:'5 Rights of IO Access.pdf',file:'5 Rights of IO Access.pdf'},
        {title:'Med Tech IO protocol.pdf',file:'Med Tech IO protocol.pdf'}
      ]
    },
    {
      id:'foley',
      title:'Foley Catheter Placement',
      content:'<p>Foley catheter placement allows accurate urine output monitoring and management of retention. In ACTT, it is especially important for burn and shock patients whose resuscitation is being guided by output trends.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Need for strict urine output measurement in burn resuscitation or shock.</li>'+
      '<li>Bladder distension or retention requiring drainage.</li>'+
      '<li>Prolonged holding where intake and output trending is clinically important.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Suspected urethral injury or pelvic trauma makes urethral catheterization unsafe until assessed.</li>'+
      '<li>Forcing the catheter against resistance can create significant injury.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Foley catheter kit, sterile supplies, lubricant, drainage bag, inflation syringe, and securement method.</li>'+
      '<li>Privacy, positioning, and enough time to maintain clean technique.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Prepare a clean sterile field and inspect the equipment before opening the system.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Use lubrication generously and insert with controlled technique rather than force.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Confirm urine return before balloon inflation whenever possible.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">Inflate the balloon only once correct positioning is assured, then secure the catheter and position the bag below bladder level.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Urine return and uncomplicated drainage support correct placement.</li>'+
      '<li>Output should then be trended as a clinical endpoint, not just observed once.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>False passage, no urine return, balloon inflation in the urethra, obstruction, and infection risk increase over time.</li>'+
      '<li>If no urine returns, troubleshoot position, tubing kinks, dehydration, or retention rather than immediately assuming proper placement.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>The Foley is your best cheap monitor of end-organ perfusion.</strong> In the absence of arterial lines, central venous pressure, and lactate-every-hour, hourly urine output is the most reliable, labour-free shock and resuscitation marker you have. Place it early in burn, septic, trauma, TBI, and DKA casualties &mdash; do not wait until "needed."</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Screen for urethral injury first.</strong> Blood at the meatus, perineal/scrotal hematoma, high-riding prostate, pelvic instability, or mechanism suggesting pelvic fracture all contraindicate blind urethral catheterization. If any of these are present, stop and escalate: suprapubic aspiration may be the only shipboard option and should be done with teleconsult support.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Set the output target up front and post it.</strong> Adult target ~0.5 mL/kg/hr (~30&ndash;50 mL/hr for most sailors); burn resuscitation target 0.5&ndash;1 mL/kg/hr; pediatric target 1 mL/kg/hr. Write the target on the bedside flow sheet so the watch acts on it without waiting for a PA recalculation.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Secure against ship motion.</strong> StatLock or equivalent Foley securement device on the thigh, with a secondary tape anchor. Traction on a poorly secured Foley during a rough transfer causes urethral injury and balloon trauma &mdash; both avoidable. Run the drainage tubing in a service loop so any pull transmits to the tape, not the urethra.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Drainage bag position is non-trivial at sea.</strong> Bag stays below bladder level at all times, including during transfers, ladder carries, and helicopter hoists. If the bag rises above the bladder, urine refluxes and infection risk rises. Secure it to the stretcher frame rather than letting it swing free.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Build an output trend sheet.</strong> Hourly in the first 8 hours of resuscitation or any instability, q2h once stable. Record volume, color (clear, concentrated, pink/red, brown), and whether the character changes. A drop from 40 mL/hr to 10 mL/hr over two consecutive readings is an action trigger.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Troubleshoot before assuming oliguria.</strong> If output suddenly drops: check for tubing kinks, dependent loops, clamped drainage, bag position, and catheter patency with a gentle flush. Only after mechanical causes are excluded is it a resuscitation problem.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Plan the catheter course, not just the insertion.</strong> For holds &gt; 48 hours, schedule daily site care (perineal cleansing), track insertion date, and watch for CAUTI signs (cloudy/foul urine, fever, new delirium). Remove as soon as the monitoring need ends &mdash; indwelling days are the strongest infection risk factor.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Rhabdomyolysis screen on dark urine.</strong> Brown/tea-colored urine in a crush, burn, or prolonged-down casualty is myoglobinuria until proven otherwise &mdash; check the dipstick for heme, push crystalloid to keep output &ge; 1 mL/kg/hr, and contact teleconsult for alkalinization guidance.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Local anesthetic gel may be used for patient comfort during insertion. In the context of burn resuscitation or shock monitoring, the Foley supports medication and fluid titration decisions rather than requiring specific procedural medications itself.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['algorithms/burn-resuscitation','algorithms/shock-management']
    },
    {
      id:'pericardiocentesis',
      title:'Emergency Pericardiocentesis',
      content:'<p>Emergency pericardiocentesis is a rare but potentially life-saving temporizing procedure for cardiac tamponade. It should only be performed when the indication is strong and the risk of not decompressing the pericardium is greater than the risk of the procedure itself.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Suspected cardiac tamponade with hemodynamic compromise.</li>'+
      '<li>Near-arrest or arrest where tamponade is strongly suspected and no faster definitive option exists.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Contraindications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Major risk arises from misdiagnosis or poor needle trajectory causing myocardial or vascular injury.</li>'+
      '<li>If ultrasound is available, it should be used because it improves target selection and reduces blind error.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Required Equipment and Setup</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Needle or catheter suitable for aspiration, syringe, sterile prep, monitoring, and ultrasound if available.</li>'+
      '<li>Clear statement of intended approach: subxiphoid, parasternal, or apical.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Step-by-Step Technique</h4>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">1</div><div class="ps-text">Select the approach based on anatomy, suspected fluid location, and ultrasound findings if available.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">2</div><div class="ps-text">Prep the site, orient the needle deliberately, and advance while aspirating in a controlled fashion.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">3</div><div class="ps-text">Once fluid is obtained and the patient improves, stop advancing and reassess.</div></div>'+
      '<div class="procedure-step"><div class="ps-num">4</div><div class="ps-text">If a catheter technique is used, secure it and continue close monitoring.</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Confirmation</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Improved blood pressure, pulse quality, or perfusion suggests clinical success.</li>'+
      '<li>Continue monitoring because pericardial fluid can reaccumulate and temporary improvement can fade quickly.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Complications and Troubleshooting</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Myocardial puncture, coronary injury, arrhythmia, failure to aspirate, and recurrent tamponade are the core risks.</li>'+
      '<li>If no fluid is obtained and the patient is not improving, reassess the diagnosis before repeated blind attempts.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>This is a last-resort, teleconsult-guided procedure for most shipboard PAs.</strong> Pericardiocentesis without ultrasound guidance is a blind needle pass toward the heart &mdash; it is almost always the wrong first move. Before proceeding, confirm tamponade clinically (Beck\'s triad: hypotension, muffled heart sounds, JVD; plus pulsus paradoxus, low voltage or electrical alternans on ECG) and rule out more treatable mimics (tension pneumothorax, massive PE, hemorrhagic shock).</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Ultrasound changes the calculus entirely.</strong> If your platform carries a portable ultrasound (SonoSite or equivalent) and you are trained in its use, a subxiphoid or parasternal view confirms effusion, localizes fluid, and guides the needle. Without ultrasound and without a crashing patient, think very hard before proceeding. Call teleconsult first if the patient is not peri-arrest.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Treat the reversible mimics first.</strong> Tension pneumothorax is far more common and is decompressed with a needle anywhere in the correct chest; do it before committing to pericardial access. A hemorrhagic shock patient with muffled-sounding heart tones in a noisy Sick Bay is not tamponade unless you have confirmatory findings.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Subxiphoid approach is the fallback when imaging is unavailable.</strong> Long spinal or pericardiocentesis needle, angled 15&ndash;30&deg; posterior and toward the left shoulder, aspirating continuously. Any fluid return that relieves symptoms is the endpoint &mdash; remove what you need to restore pressure, not all of it. Over-aspiration invites bleeding into an emptied pericardial space.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Continuous ECG monitoring is mandatory.</strong> New ST elevation, ectopy, or injury current on the needle contact confirms myocardial touch &mdash; withdraw immediately. Have defibrillator pads attached before starting because arrhythmia is a recognized complication.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Leave a catheter if you can.</strong> A Seldinger-technique pigtail catheter allows repeat drainage and avoids a second needle pass when the fluid reaccumulates &mdash; which it will. If only a needle is available, plan for repeat access and pre-position the equipment.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>MEDEVAC is not optional.</strong> Any casualty who required pericardiocentesis needs a cardiothoracic or critical care destination within hours. Initiate the highest-priority evacuation request the mission allows before you start the procedure, not after.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Document the decision and the reasoning.</strong> Because this procedure has a high complication rate and is rarely indicated, record the clinical findings, ruled-out mimics, teleconsult conversation (if obtained), and the response. This protects both the casualty and the clinician.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Any invasive procedure can precipitate hypotension, hypoxia, or worsening pain. Fluids, vasopressors, suction, oxygen, and rescue airway equipment should be considered part of the setup, not optional extras. Local anesthesia at the puncture site is appropriate if the patient is conscious and time permits.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['algorithms/cardiac-tamponade','algorithms/cardiac-arrest']
    },
    {
      id:'shoulder-reduction',
      title:'Shoulder Reduction',
      content:'<p>Shoulder dislocation management is less dramatic than airway or thoracic rescue, but it still requires discipline. Reduction should be gentle, deliberate, and built around patient relaxation, analgesia, and reassessment rather than force.</p>'+
      '<h4>Purpose and Clinical Role</h4>'+
      '<p>Reduction restores anatomy, reduces pain, and may improve neurovascular function. It also prevents unnecessary ongoing soft tissue stretch. In stable patients, it is an opportunity to practice controlled procedural setup and re-examination.</p>'+
      '<h4>Indications and Cautions</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Use in suspected shoulder dislocation when the patient is stable and life threats have been addressed.</li>'+
      '<li>Reassess distal neurovascular status before any attempt.</li>'+
      '<li>If fracture-dislocation or unclear anatomy is strongly suspected, reduce only with appropriate caution or escalate if available.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>Technique Options</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>External rotation:</strong> slow, reliable, and often successful when the patient can relax.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Scapular manipulation:</strong> useful with traction and controlled scapular movement.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Milch and FARES:</strong> traction-based methods that can work well with good patient relaxation.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Cunningham:</strong> useful in cooperative patients and may avoid sedation.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<h4>What to Avoid</h4>'+
      '<p>Avoid high-force historical methods such as Kocher or the classic Hippocratic foot-in-axilla technique. These methods carry higher risk of fracture, nerve injury, and unnecessary trauma.</p>'+
      '<h4>Post-Reduction Care</h4>'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li>Confirm reduction clinically.</li>'+
      '<li>Repeat and document neurovascular examination.</li>'+
      '<li>Immobilize, provide analgesia, and reassess for recurrent instability or associated injury.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '<div class="shipboard-callout"><div class="shipboard-callout-header" onclick="this.classList.toggle(\'expanded\');this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle(\'expanded\')"><span>&#9875;</span> At-Sea Considerations<span class="sc-chevron">&#9654;</span></div><div class="shipboard-callout-body">'+
      '<ul>'+
      '<li><strong>Reduce early.</strong> Shoulder dislocations are among the most common operational injuries on a ship (ladder falls, line handling, heavy weather). The longer a shoulder is out, the harder it is to reduce and the higher the risk of neurovascular complications. Reduce as soon as the patient is stable, NV exam is documented, and analgesia is adequate &mdash; do not wait for ideal conditions.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Rule out fracture when you can.</strong> Greater tuberosity and Hill-Sachs fractures change the reduction plan. If your platform has an imaging capability (portable X-ray or ultrasound), use it. If not, a clean mechanism (fall, tackle, abduction-external rotation) in a young sailor without crepitus, bony tenderness at other points, or severe deformity justifies reduction on clinical grounds &mdash; document your reasoning.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Position the patient for ship motion, not for convenience.</strong> Lay the casualty supine on a secured bed or exam table oriented along the ship\'s long axis. Standing or seated reduction techniques are unsafe on a rolling deck &mdash; the patient can fall or the operator can lose leverage. For prone-weight (Stimson) technique, ensure the bed is wide enough and the casualty is strapped against roll.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Use a low-intensity technique first.</strong> Scapular manipulation, Cunningham, FARES, or external rotation all produce reductions with minimal force and often without deep sedation. A cooperative, well-analgesed sailor with 0.5&ndash;1 mg/kg IV ketamine in low-dose analgesic range, plus intra-articular lidocaine if comfortable with the technique, is often enough. Reserve full procedural sedation for failed attempts or marked muscular resistance.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Procedural sedation on a ship is a two-provider commitment.</strong> If ketamine procedural sedation is used (1 mg/kg IV slow push, per ACTT), the sedation provider and the operator must be different people; a monitor with SpO<sub>2</sub>, ECG, BP cycling, and capnography (if available) runs continuously. Suction, BVM, and airway adjuncts are at the bedside before the first dose.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Pre- and post-reduction NV exam, recorded in writing.</strong> Document axillary nerve function (deltoid sensation over lateral shoulder, deltoid contraction), radial pulse, motor and sensory function in all nerve distributions before and after. A new deficit after reduction is a clinical emergency.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Immobilize in a way that survives ship movement and a working sailor\'s routine.</strong> Standard sling and swathe; avoid positions that require the casualty to hold their own arm across heavy weather. A reduced shoulder that re-dislocates on a ladder trip in the middle of the night is a preventable failure.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>Plan follow-up to the next alongside.</strong> A reduced primary dislocation needs orthopedic follow-up within 1&ndash;2 weeks; document the reduction technique, success, post-reduction NV exam, and return-to-duty limitations in the medical record. Restrict heavy lifting and overhead work aggressively in the interim &mdash; a second dislocation at sea is much harder to manage.</li>'+
      '<li><strong>If reduction fails after two gentle attempts with adequate sedation, stop.</strong> Do not force the issue; immobilize in a position of comfort, analgesia, and request MEDEVAC or slow-boat transfer to an orthopedic asset. Forced reduction attempts cause fracture, labral injury, and nerve damage.</li>'+
      '</ul>'+
      '</div></div>'+
      '<h4>Medication Needs</h4>'+
      '<p>Ketamine is often useful because it preserves blood pressure and can support painful procedures or restraint scenarios. Midazolam can reduce anxiety and blunt ketamine emergence reactions, but it increases respiratory depression risk when combined with opioids. Opioids may be useful in selected procedures but should be titrated carefully, especially when respiratory reserve is limited.</p>',
      relatedLinks:['medications/ketamine','medications/midazolam','medications/morphine']
    }
  ],
  postProcedure:{
    title:'Post-Procedure Reassessment and Ongoing Care',
    content:'<p>A procedure is only complete when its effect has been verified and its consequences are being managed. The patient may deteriorate because the procedure failed, because the procedure succeeded only temporarily, or because the procedure introduced a new problem.</p>'+
    '<ul>'+
    '<li>Ask immediately: did the intervention fix the target problem?</li>'+
    '<li>Recheck vitals, oxygenation, perfusion, pain, and mental status.</li>'+
    '<li>Assess the device itself: tube, line, catheter, or drainage system can fail mechanically after technically correct placement.</li>'+
    '<li>Document the time, indication, key findings, and early response.</li>'+
    '<li>If evacuation is delayed, convert immediately to a maintenance plan that includes monitoring intervals, troubleshooting steps, and handover points.</li>'+
    '</ul>'
  },
  commonErrors:{
    title:'Common Errors Across Procedures',
    content:'<ul>'+
    '<li>Starting a procedure without a clearly stated indication.</li>'+
    '<li>Poor setup with no backup plan or rescue equipment ready.</li>'+
    '<li>Inadequate landmarking leading to wrong-site placement.</li>'+
    '<li>Technical focus so narrow that the team misses physiologic deterioration.</li>'+
    '<li>Failure to confirm success using the right physiologic markers.</li>'+
    '<li>Poor securement, leading to dislodgement during movement.</li>'+
    '<li>Assuming the problem is solved after a technically successful placement and forgetting the next care burden.</li>'+
    '</ul>'
  },
  learningObjectives:{
    title:'What the Learner Should Be Able to Do After This Chapter',
    content:'<ul>'+
    '<li>Recognize when a major ACTT procedure is required and when it is not.</li>'+
    '<li>Prepare the patient, team, and equipment in a structured way before starting.</li>'+
    '<li>Perform the key steps in the correct order for the major airway, thoracic, access, monitoring, and selected rescue procedures.</li>'+
    '<li>Confirm success, identify failure early, and troubleshoot common complications.</li>'+
    '<li>Maintain the intervention safely during delayed MEDEVAC or prolonged holding.</li>'+
    '</ul>'
  }
};
